post_text:
#HealthyAtSchool Guidance Updated

Kentucky‚Äôs #HealthyAtSchool guidance now states that all students and staff should wear a mask at all times while they are in school, even if they are 6 feet apart. The guidance document can be found here- https://education.ky.gov/comm/Documents/Safety%20Expectations_FINAL%20DOC.pdf

This updated guidance comes from public health officials and the Kentucky Department of Education.

"The use of cloth face coverings (masks) should be required by all students and staff at all times while in the building or on the bus, unless medically waivered," the new #HealthyAtSchool guidance says. "Students and staff should only lower their masks while actively eating or drinking."

McCracken County Schools want to thank our families, students and staff for being cooperative, understanding and flexible as we continue to navigate a new school year. #McCrackenProud

post_text:
MCHS Culinary Program Named To Sullivan University‚Äôs High School Programs of Distinction

The McCracken County High School culinary arts program has been named to the Sullivan University‚Äôs High School Programs of Distinction (formerly the Elite 50 program) from Sullivan University, Louisville, Kentucky. The award is an exclusive group of high schools from across the country. This is the third year in a row that the program at MCHS has received this prestigious award.

The Sullivan University‚Äôs High School Programs of Distinction is comprised of high schools that excel in the areas of culinary arts, baking and pastry arts, and/or hospitality management. Some are state and national competition winners from ProStart, SkillsUSA and Family Career and Community Leaders of America (FCCLA). These schools have established strong hospitality enrollment and influence in their community.

Ashley Woodruff is the culinary instructor at McCracken County High School. #McCrackenProud

McCracken County High School lost two amazing educators this month-CD McCord & Kacy York. Both ladies would spend their own money to meet the needs of their students, whether it was a meal delivered during NTI, a candy incentive, a new pair of shoes or a Homecoming dress.

A fund has been set up at the high school that will continue this work. Shirts and decals with the design below are available for purchase at http://www.shopsilkworm.com/mchsfundraiser
All profits will be split between the two funds.
#LoveLikeCD #CareLikeKacy

Donations can also be made to:
MCHS Memorial Fund
6530 New HWY 60 West
Paducah, KY 42001

post_text: McCracken County High School sophomore Hailey Williams has been accepted to the Craft Academy for Excellence in Science and Mathematics at Morehead State University, class of 2022. The Craft Academy is a dual-credit residential high school for academically exceptional Kentucky students. Craft Academy challenges students to excel at their highest level through project-based STEM+X courses and hands-on learning experiences, with emphasis on innovation, design and creativity, and civic and regional engagement. Congratulations, Hailey! #McCrackenProud

Paducah Bank
May 12 at 2:16 AM ¬∑

TEEN OF THE YEAR UPDATE: April Riley, 2017 Teen of the Year, is a junior at Murray State University. April is majoring in Public & Community Health with a focus in Health Education. She is a member of the Honors College at MSU and has studied abroad in Jamaica, England, and Greece. She will graduate in 2021.

In 2017 when April won the top teen award presented by The Paducah Sun and Paducah Bank, she commented that she was grateful for the financial struggle she had experienced. "It motivated me to work hard, because I knew nothing in life would be handed to me," said April, a McCracken County High School senior and student in the Commonwealth Middle College program.

Read more about April's journey since being named Teen of the Year here:

https://www.paducahbank.com/Learn/Whats-Happening/News/April-RIley-Teen-of-the-year

post_text:
This summer will be one of our most challenging ever for the Red Cross blood program. With schools out and some businesses unable to host their normal summer blood drives, there is a great need for additional sponsors and individual coordinators.

The Leaders Save Lives program offers a $50 incentive for any high school or college student who coordinates a blood drive that collects at least 25 pints of blood (see attachment). Any student interested in coordinating a blood drive this summer should contact our local Red Cross contact ASAP. Please call or email: Anthony Tinin at 270-853-4349 or anthony.tinin@redcross.org.

post_text:
Mason Wooten a junior at McCracken County High School, earned the highest possible ACT composite score of 36. This is his second time to score a perfect 36 (first time was his sophomore year).

Of 2019 high school graduates, 4,879 out of nearly 1.8 million students who took the ACT scored a composite 36. The test includes four sections ‚Äì English, mathematics, reading and science ‚Äì and each is scored on a scale of up to 36. The total composite score is the average of the four tests.

post_text: Today, Governor Beshear shared his recommendation that Kentucky schools will finish the remainder of the 2019-20 school year utilizing NTI instruction. Though students and teachers will not be in our buildings, McCracken County Schools will continue to provide meals, learning opportunities and support for the remainder of the academic year. Details regarding graduations and other end of the year processes will be published in the coming weeks. We will continue to update parents and students with information as work through these unprecedented times.

Tonight at McCracken County High School.

To honor the MCHS spring sports teams who have not been able to compete, (and specifically the seniors on those teams), we are Lighting Up the Campus! Starting at 8pm tomorrow, April 20, you can come in the main entrance and follow the pre-determined path to see the fields lit up and some special messages from MCHS to students. Vehicles will not be stopping.

Tonight we will honor spring senior athletes for: baseball, softball, tennis, track, trap shooting, and bass fishing. #McCrackenProud

Tonight at McCracken County High School.

To honor the MCHS spring sports teams who have not been able to compete, (and specifically the seniors on those teams), we are Lighting Up the Campus! Starting at 8pm tomorrow, April 20, you can come in the main entrance and follow the pre-determined path to see the fields lit up and some special messages from MCHS to students. Vehicles will not be stopping.

Tonight we will honor spring senior athletes for: baseball, softball, tennis, track, trap shooting, and bass fishing. #McCrackenProud

Following Governor Beshear's recommendation that all Kentucky Schools stop-in person instruction, McCracken County Schools Non-Traditional Instruction will be extended through Friday, April 17.

The week of April 6 is our scheduled Spring Break, so there will be no NTI assignments during that week.

March 16-March 20 NTI Days
March 23-March 27 NTI Days
March 30-April 3 NTI Days
April 6- April 10 Spring Break
April 13- April 17 NTI Days

This week our staff served over 23,500 meals to the students of McCracken County. We will continue to try and offer meals as we have over the past week. As the circumstances change, we may have to modify the manner in which this is done. As of today, we will continue utilizing our buses to deliver meals. If you would like to receive a meal please visit www.mccracken.kyschools.us for more information.

While students are utilizing NTI days we will continue to provide support and answer questions. Please, feel free to reach out to your child‚Äôs teacher or principal daily from 8:00 a.m.- 3:00 p.m.
text:

The week of April 6 is our scheduled Spring Break, so there will be no NTI assignments during that week.

March 16-March 20 NTI Days
March 23-March 27 NTI Days
March 30-April 3 NTI Days
April 6- April 10 Spring Break
April 13- April 17 NTI Days

This week our staff served over 23,500 meals to the students of McCracken County. We will continue to try and offer meals as we have over the past week. As the circumstances change, we may have to modify the manner in which this is done. As of today, we will continue utilizing our buses to deliver meals. If you would like to receive a meal please visit www.mccracken.kyschools.us for more information.

While students are utilizing NTI days we will continue to provide support and answer questions. Please, feel free to reach out to your child‚Äôs teacher or principal daily from 8:00 a.m.- 3:00 p.m.

This afternoon, Governor Andy Beshear issued a strong request that all schools in the state of Kentucky close effective Monday, March 16th for a period of two weeks. It is extremely important, as the governor emphasized, that all students are expected to be in attendance tomorrow, March 13th, so that they can receive instruction on how to complete school work in a non-traditional school setting.

Tomorrow at 8:00 a.m. the McCracken County Schools Board of Education is considering approving the Non-Traditional Instruction (NTI) application. We expect to start NTI days on Monday, March 16.

Again, I will continue to update parents with information as it becomes available. Please check our district website for up-to-date information- http://www.mccracken.kyschools.us/COVID-19.aspx

Steve Carter, Superintendent
McCracken County Public Schools

McCracken County Schools had 32 nominees! #McCrackenProud

On March 5, more than 300 educators, family, friends, and students were on hand to cheer and recognize the 63 nominees in the Regional Educators Awards and Scholarship Program at the Clemens Fine Arts Center.

Deserving faculty, administrators and staff from throughout the Jackson Purchase and Southern Illinois were nominated for awards in four categories: distinguished faculty for grades pre-kindergarten through fifth, distinguished faculty for grades sixth through 12th, distinguished administrators, and the Cornelia Reece Unsung Hero Staff Award, named for the wife of WKCTC President Anton Reece.

Lone Oak Middle School's K-8 Chess Team took 2nd Place at the Quad A Regional Team Chess Championships in Marion, KY last Saturday. Team members- Carsen Hammonds, Cy Hines and Sofia Rinella.

The remarkable achievement was accomplished with only 3 players (4 players make a complete team). Carsen Hammonds and Cy Hines won 1st Place Individual trophies as Co-Champions, each having achieved perfect scores of 4-0.

The entire K-8 LOMS Chess Team will now compete at the State Team Championship on March 7th. The 4 person team will be: Owen Cody, Manav Shah, Carsen Hammonds, and Cy Hines. Sofia Rinella will be designated as an Alternate competing in the Alternate section.

The K-8 Chess Team has won 1st place at every other tournament this season. #McCrackenProud

post_text: McCracken County High School students, Noah Ellis and Abby Hefner, spoke at the ASAP Advisory meeting today to tell about the efforts being made by the FCCLA Taking Down Tobacco Student Ambassador Team. Ambassadors have delivered the peer led education to 25 classrooms at the high school as well as 3 elementary schools. They are telling their peers about the harmful effects that come from a nicotine addiction. They have also been advocating to legislators to write stricter laws to keep e-cigarettes out of the hands of youth. They will partner later this month with the Mustang Youth Service Center to carry the message to a wider audience which includes classrooms campus wide.

post_text:
Late Saturday night (Feb.1), Reidland Middle School administrators were informed of a potential threat of violence made against Reidland Middle.

McCracken County Public Schools is working with the McCracken County Sheriff‚Äôs Office to investigate the matter and will be pursuing full legal action.

The safety and security of our students and staff is always our top priority and we take all threats seriously, as does the McCracken County Sheriff‚Äôs Office.

This is a timely reminder for our entire school community that threatening or concerning behavior or language should always be reported to authorities and we thank those that brought this information forward.

The Daughters of the American Revolution (DAR) Youth Citizenship Medal was established to foster among school children a greater appreciation of the qualities of citizenship Americans must possess if our country is to remain sovereign and independent. Three McCracken County High School students received the Youth Citizenship Medal- Bailey Bowland (11th grade), Ava Kelly (10th grade), and Hannah Bryan (9th grade).

This medal is presented to a student who exemplifies the qualities of honor, service, courage, leadership, and patriotism.

post_text:
McCracken County High School Wins First Place at WKCTC's 2020 President's Cup

Eight regional high schools competed in the 2020 President's Cup Academic Bowl held at West Kentucky Community and Technical College January 9.

McCracken County High School took home the top prize with Calloway County and Paducah Tilghman high schools winning second and third place trophies, respectively.

Other participating Kentucky high schools were Ballard Memorial, Graves County, Marshall County, Murray and St. Mary high schools.

The WKAA competition consisted of individual written assessments in arts/humanities, language arts, mathematics, science, social studies, and quick recall matches.

The top five written assessment winners were chosen from each category. First place winners from MCHS were:

Arts/Humanities - Rachel Hwang, McCracken County

Social Studies - Noah Ellis, McCracken County

The Governor's Cup will be held at the district, regional and state levels. This year's state competition will be held March 14-16 in Louisville.

post_text:
Congrats Jade Tinin & Ronnie Jones!

Mark Bryant & the Bryant Law Center are proud partners of Mustang Madness and basketball across the Bluegrass State. Bryant Law Center created the Louise Bryant Scholarship seven years ago for the inaugural Mustang Madness. Bryant Law Center is proud to continue the Louise Bryant Achievement of Excellence Award again this year. A female and male recipient is selected based upon community involvement, overall student activity, and overall character. Mark Bryant‚Äôs mother, Louise Bryant, served on the faculty of Paducah Tilghman High School and greatly influenced many youth in Western Ky. For years, she was in a variety of activities at Grace Episcopal Church, was a Paducah Ambassador and a volunteer for the Red Cross and National Quilt Museum. She was also a member of the Delphic Club, a Duchess of Paducah and a Kentucky Colonel. The 2020 Louise Bryant Achievement of Excellence award goes to Jade Tinin and Ronnie Jones. #McCrackenProud
